Welcome to Computing Logic!  
Computing Logic overlaps the fields of philosophical logic and and mathematical logic within the field of computer science to more easily test hypotheses.

Within the 7 modules of the Computing Logic (SDEV) section you will learn the basics of how to to use algorithms, logic development and flowcharting as tools to document computer logic.  Important math concepts to computing logic includes: base numbering systems, truth tables, logic operators, and relational operators, order of precedence, decision trees, security and different language approaches including scripting.

Focusing upon the logic layer within the sub-field of Computer Science called Software Development (SDEV) allows you to focus on how to better tell a computer what to do, rather than the mechanics of how the data is stored physically in a computer in code.  Some concepts of coding and the physical layer will be introduced so that you can determine if you wish to go further in that area with more formal programming methods which combine the physical and logic layers of creating a program. 

